segments.text: I can think of some regions that live under the ocean.
I think a great place for nightclubs, for instance.
I can think of great nightclubs.
There's a beautiful one in the Gulf of Eilat that the Israelis have.
And you sit down there underneath, looking up through glass windows and everything going on in that beautiful part of the branch of the Red Sea.
I can think of condominiums for people with emphysema living under one atmosphere, extra pressure.
two atmospheres of pressure, they could live perfectly normal lives, couldn't they?
That's all they need.
Why should people go around gasping for breath in the last 10 years of their life when they could live under one extra atmosphere and breathe normally?
And this might be a reasonable sort of location for a condominium under a couple of atmospheres of pressure down some beautiful parts of Florida Straits.
And it makes it much easier to build and less dangerous if it's under water, where the pressure is equalized on the inside and outside.
But as far as people just inhabiting the bottom of the ocean for reasons of space, I'd rather consider taking Jupiter apart and making some more planets.
I think that's more feasible.
That's a big engineering job.
You can make dozens and dozens of planets.
I'd like to be around for that one, by the way.
Well, maybe you don't want to do that.
Maybe you want to do is just add a little bit to Mars from Jupiter, you see, to make it more habitable.
It's a real chemical engineering job, too, changing that ammonia into something else and getting water and so on, getting a decent atmosphere.
Were you surprised, by the way,
with reports coming back from Mars in terms of the satellite pictures or the landing pictures we're receiving now?
I've been in Baja, California.
I've been looking at Martian landscape for quite a while down there.
But what are these like?
They're boulder-strewn, aren't they?
They're boulder-strewn, and the possibility that many of them are cut by water.
Oh, yeah, sure.
Well, obviously Mars has its ice caps of some sort.
It has water or some condensable fluid.
That's some condensable gas.
And it certainly probably had more in the past.
No, I don't think I was particularly surprised.
Not that I was believing the canals of Mars, but I think it's perfectly real.
What I was really surprised on at was the surface of Venus.

I mean, it really didn't occur to me, or I guess anybody else, that with such a dense atmosphere as Venus, and even with such tremendously high wind velocities, that the boundary layer should be so thick that there was no wind at the surface, essentially windless at the surface.
I think that was strange.
All right.
I wanted to ask you two or three questions about aquaculture.
Do you see the future in aquaculture and such things as planned oyster beds, or do you see it in terms of mining what we always classified before as seaweeds, or both?
Well, you know, we start out with
I'm thinking we've just thought of agriculture.
Of course, every place in the world, other than the United States, has conducted it for a long time.
Japanese, there's tremendous industries all through Indonesia.
Almost everybody in the world knows more about agriculture than we do.
We start out as though, now we're going to solve all these problems.
I was looking at East Pakistan, and East Pakistan produces in its ponds.
Now, this is freshwater.
Ponds and bills.
And about as much fish, that little country produced about as much fish as a third of the US catch, just from its ponds and bill.
Oh, it's essentially culture.
Well, hell, everybody knows more about this than we do.
And so I'm not quite sure what you mean.
Why don't you ask me about a future of it?
If you ask me, is the United States going to learn from anybody, I'm not so sure.
They're going to go through all the difficulties of trying to solve the problems all by themselves.

They're going to make it so expensive that the only thing that can possibly be used is high luxury food that has nothing to do about the impact of protein food on the world's supply, as far as I can see.

Now, it does seem to me that we're trying to jump, if you look at, you're an agricultural historian, and I may be quite wrong about this history, but it seems to me like there's a sequential series from the hunting economy to the gathering economy to what I would call the ranch economy.

where you use preferred herbivores to crop the land with their own energy, to the farm in which you start to raise the supplies for your domestic animals, to the battery culture in which you bring food in to immobilized or essentially immobilized creatures from whatever worldwide sources are necessary.
Now, we're immediately leaping to that last step, the battery culture.
But ocean is a poor environment.
It's a thin broth that has trace.
The food is highly dispersed in a dense medium.
It's a million times more dilute than, say, a grass field, a field of grass.
A million times more dilute.
Traditionally, and even today, in modern society, where you have a poor environment, you use ranging techniques.
You send your preferred creature out onto this.
You don't use diesel oil.
You do a little bit of diesel oil to cultivate or gather food and bring it into them.
You let them burn some part of the crop that's sparsely distributed out here, and then you have a roundup.
You bring them back in some way, and you have made some net gain.
Well, the one interesting thing you have in the ocean is this number of species that will round themselves up, all the anadromous fishes, the ones that come in and spawn.
And some of these are primitive feeders, some of the shads.
The hilsa, the Indian shad, is a particularly fine food fish.
So it seems to me like a sensible step would really be ranging.
That is, you culture a population which you now turn loose in its thin environment to graze it and then to return to you, you see.
And you can do some predator control and maybe some seeding of sorts, just essentially the way you do it in rangeland management.
essentially the same sort of level.
But our effort here is to or leap all of these steps that we've taken 3,000 years to go through on land and go right to battery culture.
Well, I don't know.
The problems, obviously, of animal husbandry, once you get to these more concentrated levels, has totally been a disease.
And we have spent a tremendous lot of time.
This is a disease of any concentration of organisms.
And we spent a lot of time solving this in the case of our preferred species on land.
Each one of these organisms in the ocean is going to have a series of disasters.
We try battery culture.
Exactly the same nature.
One new disease after another.
And all the immunization, all the research that has to go behind it.
But in the United States, I don't think we'll progress beyond luxury food.
Because it's not necessary for us to increase the protein supply that much?
Well, I think the increased protein supply around the world, and Ravel may have talked to you about this, is something of a delusion anyway.
But actually, the world is equally short on fats and oils, probably more limiting nutrients.
But no, because we'll make things too expensive.

Every time we build a lobster industry, we'll have to build a sewage disposal plant just to get rid of the seawater that it went through, and so on, that went through that lobster culture, and so forth.
And just the manpower involved in things is going to make it impossible to culture anything except luxury species.
I think we'll find out some interesting things.
OK. Now.

But the ranging of using some sort of primitive feeder like shad to go forth into the ocean and concentrate this thin soup of the ocean and bring it back to us, now that seems to be a much more viable approach.
But you don't think we'll choose?
I don't think we'll choose, no.
I want you to describe how fish population histories can be inferred from fish scales found in sediments.
I wasn't sure I understood that.
And what ecological and evolutionary implications does this technique have?
Well, it's somewhat unlimited, I think, eventually.
But let me describe the technique to start with.
In a few places, the ocean bottom is continuously building up, as you know, and continuously moving and doing all these things that we
began to understand from seafloor spreading and continental drift.
But in a few places around the world, the bottom waters, usually in near shore basins, are anaerobic or anoxic.
They have no oxygen in them, and nothing lives there.
Even though over most of the ocean, the sediments are raining down every year.
There are things living there that mix them up, and so the time resolution that you can get is of the order of 10,000 years at the best.
The sediments are mixed continuously.
But in these regions, they're laid down in layers that you can identify year by year.
You can put your finger on it and say, within a few years, that year is the year zero right there.
That's what the sediments were laid down in the year zero.

you go back in time become somewhat less certain but you can just count back and you can check your count with radioactive dating well such sediments exist on land the whole monterey formation and you can split it open and you can see peppered with fish scales and other kinds of debris diatoms form and effort so you know something in that year of what the pacific was doing or what the ocean was doing
and something about what fish were present, you see, because you can identify these scales.
You can date these scales, and you can tell how old they were and how fast they were growing, how, you know, what species it was, you know, how old the fish was and how fast it had grown.
So you know a great deal, and you know it for that year, exactly.
Well, the kind of Rosetta Stone in this whole business is, of course, if you try this, how well does this agree to the known history?
And when we went through that exercise, we found it agreed very well with the known history, where we really know what the populations of the pelagic fish are out here.

Our results from looking at these sediments and analyzing the number of scales per year coming down, totally independently, gives us the same curve of the variation between the number of hake, the number of anchovies, the number of saris, and the number of sardines.
This gives us confidence we can make these same kind of counts back into the past, as far as we want, and see what has been the relationship between these fish.
And what we find is something very surprising.

We find that the sardine, which was the dominant phlegic fish here when man first started his fisheries, has never been here for long periods of time, but only for short bursts, maybe eight times in the last 1,600 years has it been here in quantity.
The anchovy harbor has been here continuously over the whole time, you see.
So it's really quite an interesting picture.
And my earlier parts of my conversation, when I said society would seem to be unable to act on information, this is very powerful information.
You would really never have expected to have such a real insight into the way these species interacted in the past and what their natural abundance was and how it fluctuated.

And now to conceive that a fishery on the Anchovy, a species that has maintained a sizable population here for at least the last 1600 years, would be the same as a fishery on the sardine, a species that was never able to maintain a sizable population here for more than 40 or 50 or 80 years at a time.
and then only a few periods, is asinine.
I mean, you couldn't expect it to have the same result, fishery on a transient species and fishery on a permanent species.
So in my earlier remarks, I said I thought we had gotten exquisite answers on some of these problems that society had enunciated as a worthwhile problem to work on.
And yet the disappointment is, of course, not that they don't act on this, but they don't consider it even in their actions, to reiterate.
OK. What about in terms of evolutionary implications?
Do you foresee being able to apply
to see the evolution in general of fishes and fish species from this kind of?
Well, of course, that's the traditional way of going because their 10,000 year resolution has no particular consequence.
But to see the interrelationships between the microorganisms, for instance.
So we know how the Pacific was behaving when the sardine was here.
and how it behaved when they changed from one species to another.

We'll eventually know what environmental conditions mediated these shifts between species, because we can see how much mid-Pacific influence there was, how strong the California current was, how much subtropical water was flowing up, how strong was the countercurrent.
And do this on a year-by-year basis.
That's a huge job.
We have to identify all the diatoms and foraminifera in these little thin layers, seven tenths of a millimeter thick.

But you see, if we now go to a place like the Bay of Bengal, and the Indians are going to start a fishery, say, on their astrology, wouldn't it be a wonderful thing to be able to tell them, is that a permanent thing?
species here?
Is it occasionally replaced by others?
Is it just a transient species?
How steady is the population?
How steady has it been for 2,000 years?
These are big answers for people who want to guide their fisheries in some rational way.
Would you judge us to be proceeding cautiously enough
are not cautiously enough in developing the sea.
What do you mean by us?
Well, us as Americans.
Would you encourage us to exercise more caution or less caution?
I think caution is the wrong word there.
I would advise us to use more rationality.
Caution is really totally the wrong word.
For example, we're going to
The whole matter of domestic waste is floating in the ocean.
What do you want to call caution there?
Caution is putting out a billion dollars in Los Angeles to build tertiary treatment plants, is it?
$300 per, $500 per capita when we have so many social needs?
Is that caution?
No, all the evidence is the ocean is perfectly competent to absorb these kind of wastes.
That's its business.
Absorbing organic material.
So I'm not quite sure what the cost is.
Rationality is the word.
Yes.
We need a great deal more.
A great deal more.
We need people other than Cousteau advising the government on what to do.
He has reasons to scare people to death.
Which are?
Funds for his institution.
It's going to be extremely costly.
to society as a whole.
It doesn't take a balanced viewpoint.
There's pictures of us climbing to the highest mountain tops and clutching our throats because we're dying of anoxia because we've killed all the phytoplankton.
No evidence.
No evidence.
Now, what do you see your role in the future of oceanography?
How do you perceive yourself in the coming future?
Well, I'd like to know.
I have no idea.
I've always been enthusiastic and melioristic, I guess is the word.
Somewhere between optimistic and pessimistic.
I think melioristic is optimism, but only you have to do something about it and just have it happen.
I've, to some real degree, right at the moment, lost confidence that
Defense can be influenced very promptly.
But our political system is such that it really is not able to respond to the evidence.
It's acclimation, government by acclimation of some sort.
A politician moves the beat.
causes the least stir in some way, gets the fewest people mad at him.
And I really think maybe we just can't act this way.
Now, maybe we can afford not to act this way.
We can afford to put an extra billion dollars in sewer plants in every major city along the coast for no purpose.
And maybe we need to.
Maybe it's the WPA of sorts.
Maybe it's the science that we've worked on as a WPA of sorts at a higher level.
Maybe the WPA concept has evolved so that I'm nothing but a WPA worker making bridges in some unknown creek in some unknown mountain that will never be seen again.
I dislike thinking this, but I'm
beginning to wonder if the WPA concept hasn't spread quite a bit.
It worries me to see this wake of scientists who have tried to serve this country and unable to serve it.
A great number of people that worked on desalination just announced today that something you knew 20 years ago when the desalination program on the OSW was established.
that it was impossible to do this for agricultural water.
And you could make that calculation in an instant.
At that time, you knew that if the ocean were freshwater, that is, if it were given to you at sea level, it would have very little effect on our utilization of water in these United States.
It's too big a continent.
But I'm not a bit sure.
I came to the conclusion that
Israel was full of smart people.
They had reason to be conservative with their resources.
They're screwed up as we are.
They've brought our culture there anyway.
They are a piece of the United States, more or less.
They have the same screw-up as we have.
So I'm not quite sure.
Mexico?
Mexico looks pretty good, I think.
They don't necessarily follow the tradition.
They can have their microondas instead of stringing copper wires around forever because Anaconda insists on it or whatever.
They can have their communication system by some totally modern approach rather than by the conventional ones.
Can they conduct a fishery that way?
Yes.
These are the countries that are going to maybe profit from this research.
They're starting an anchovy fishery.
And they're going to start it on the basis of the data we got to try to help the people of California.
Well, survival is the fittest.
I think the same old laws still act.
Are you still intimately involved, by the way, with Israel?
I don't know what you mean, intimately.
We're putting a breakwater over there.
Yeah, I mean, is that process still going on?
Oh, sure.
Okay.
Yeah.
Sure, they're bright people, but they're screwed up also.
They have their own political system that's copied much after ours.
They also can't do the rational thing.
What role do you see for Scripps' institution in the future of oceanography?
Oh, well, I think Scripps will be a leader for a long time.
He'll be a leader for the simple reason that there are a lot of bright people here.
foreseeable future, I think that it has to avoid getting into huge projects which totally dominate it in many ways.
Say, for instance, the CERI project.
It certainly may have a role in that.
But I think it's unhealthy for very large projects to dominate an institution like that, unless they're very highly generalized ones.
I think it should have a better role somehow in advising the government.
I've been looking at a series of reports lately in which we really act.
I collect together various groups of scientists as rather fixed panels to review various research projects, various proposals, and really criticize them.
And I think that's having a salutary
I think that's working rather well, but it's a rather small scale.
I think maybe that's the way one might act.
Really get competent people together so when Lockheed or API or somebody like that has a big project, there's a competent review by competent scientists that are undertaken to
really see if it makes sense, so that you don't get in this funny situation of they're still dealing with small-scale hydrodynamics when it's really very large-scale hydrodynamics.
Do you think that the role of oceanography, or restructuring oceanography, if I may use that word, or development of the oceans... Is explosive.
Sure.
I think that...
It still suffers, like most research in the United States, from the final and enveloping shock wave of Alamogordo, which is, if you throw enough money at it, you can solve it.
That was foreseeable, wasn't it?
You put a billion dollars in, you released this vast amount of energy.
But somehow, the important thing is
I remember the days when I was peripherally associated with these great men who were responsible for nuclear energy.
Karam, Gamow, Fermi, all these people.
And I remember the excitement there was at that time.
Here was really the new world.
Columbus entering the new world.
Many ideas.
Nobody had the idea it was going to be just nuclear reactors in the conventional time.
Today, there were all kinds.
with ideas of how you use this nuclear energy, including plowshare, just as an explosive.
We've kind of lost that sense of adventure.
Everybody's treading too lightly.
Somebody else is going to have to do it, French possibly.
I don't know.
They seem more adventurous right now.
They have a different kind of a government, too.
40 people can argue about something rather than just on 40 sides, rather than 20 on two sides.
All kinds of viewpoints can be raised in a Napoleonic society that can't be raised in a common law, English common law society, just because of the influence, I think, of our judiciary system.
The influence of our judiciary system?
Of our judiciary system, our advocative system.
Oh, OK. All right.
then you conceive...
It's a curious output, as I understand it.
You probably know much more about this, and your wife probably knows more than you do about it.
But it seems to me that a result of the Napoleonic system is you try to get at the truth, not just...
The gray area is considered.
Pros and cons.
It's a court of equity rather than a court of law, if I use these terms correctly.
In the United States, all these things are decided as though they were a court of law, either right or wrong, one or the other.
Science isn't that way.
